article.headline: Arkansas State 90, New Mexico State 76
article.story: JONESBORO, Ark. (AP) -- Arkansas State rode balanced scoring and hot shooting in the second half to beat New Mexico State 90-76 in a Sun Belt Conference game Saturday. The Indians (15-12, 7-7 SBC) trailed 45-40 at halftime, but shot 52.8 percent after the break to pull away from the conference's last-place team (5-23, 1-14). New Mexico State has lost 10 straight and is headed for its worst season in 20 years. The Aggies finished 7-20 in 1984-85. The Aggies finish the season at home Tuesday with a non-conference game against Texas-Pan American. Arkansas State was led by Marcus Ardison's 19 points. Dewarick Spencer added 18, J.J. Montgomery had 14 and Jerry Nichols put in 13 off the bench. The Indians were able to go deep into their bench, playing all 14 who dressed. New Mexico State went cold in the second half. The Aggies shot 59.3 percent in the first half, but hit just 8 of 28 shots in the second half, including just 2 of 17 3-pointers. Duane John provided most of the scoring with 24 points. Josh Jenkins had 14 and Jeff Jones, the lone front-line player in the Aggies' four-guard starting lineup, had 11. John hit 7 of 13 shots and was 4-for-8 on 3s. Jenkins also had four 3-pointers, but as has been a season-long trend, the Aggies could not make plays in the second half. Arkansas State also outrebounded the Aggies 43-34. New Mexico State led a 15-6 lead with 14:55 left in the first half and still lead 45-40 at the end of the first 20 minutes. The Indians tied the game with five straight points to start the second half and took their first lead of the game at 49-47. The Indians used a 22-7 run early in the second half to take control and built a 69-54 with 10:02 left. The lead grew to 79-61 with 6:39 remaining.
